Economic Structure\
\
1. Trump administration imposed a 50% tariff on Brazilian coffee imports and raised duties on other coffee-producing countries (2025-08-16): Sharp coffee tariffs disrupted supply chains for U.S. businesses and consumers while pressuring foreign producers, using trade policy in ways that can raise domestic costs and strain international economic relations.\
\
2. Environmental Protection Agency under Trump appointees moved to rescind the 2009 endangerment finding for greenhouse gases (2025-08-18): Undoing the core legal basis for federal climate regulation weakened the government\'92s ability to limit emissions, favoring fossil fuel interests over long-term environmental and public health protections.\
\
3. Health Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. terminated 22 federally funded mRNA vaccine development projects worth $500 million (2025-08-18): Canceling major mRNA research investments over ideological objections undermined evidence-based public health innovation and redirected federal resources away from proven vaccine platforms.\
\
4. Treasury Department under the Trump administration rewrote standards for renewable energy project eligibility for tax credits (2025-08-19): Tightening criteria for clean-energy tax credits threatened the financial viability of many projects, tilting federal support away from renewables and toward incumbent energy interests.\
\
5. U.S. government and Intel pursued converting Chips and Science Act funding into a non-voting equity stake in Intel (2025-08-19): Seeking an equity position in a major chipmaker marked a shift toward direct state ownership in strategic industry, raising questions about corporate influence, risk-sharing, and democratic oversight of industrial policy.\
\
6. Congress and President Trump enacted a budget reconciliation bill projected to trigger large automatic cuts to Medicare and Medicaid (2025-08-19): A deficit-increasing bill set up nearly $1.5 trillion in future cuts to Medicare and Medicaid, shifting fiscal burdens onto seniors and low-income people and shrinking core social safety nets.\
\
7. U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services issued a new policy requiring more subjective, holistic evaluations of citizenship applicants\'92 moral character (2025-08-19): Embedding broad behavioral and \'93societal norms\'94 tests into naturalization decisions increased discretion and the risk of bias, making access to citizenship more contingent on officials\'92 value judgments.\
\
8. Trump administration proposed a rule to bar Public Service Loan Forgiveness for employees of entities deemed to undermine national security or American values (2025-08-20): Tying student loan forgiveness eligibility to employers\'92 perceived alignment with national values politicized a financial benefit and could chill work at disfavored organizations.\
\
9. Immigration and Customs Enforcement planned to spend over $2.4 million on customized SUVs and militarized branding without open bidding (2025-08-20): Awarding noncompetitive contracts for militarized vehicles with propaganda-style slogans raised transparency concerns and illustrated how enforcement agencies can channel public funds into image-building.\
\
10. Federal Emergency Management Agency required disaster aid applicants to have email addresses following a federal move away from paper payments (2025-08-22): Conditioning emergency aid on digital access risked excluding people without internet or email, effectively turning technological gaps into barriers to basic relief after disasters.\
\
11. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention rescinded embargoes on importing civets, Lucky Bamboo in water, and Haitian goat-skin handicrafts (2025-08-22): Lifting long-standing health-related import bans in the name of deregulation reduced trade barriers but also shifted reliance onto updated science and other safeguards to manage disease risks.\
\
12. Trump administration clawed back over $12 million in federal grants from California\'92s public health program over alleged promotion of gender ideology (2025-08-21): Revoking health grants on ideological grounds punished a state program\'92s content choices, using federal funding leverage to enforce cultural preferences in public health services.\
\
13. Trump administration canceled union contracts for hundreds of thousands of federal workers via executive order after a favorable appeals ruling (2025-08-22): Voiding collective bargaining agreements for about 400,000 federal employees weakened organized labor in the civil service and concentrated managerial power over working conditions.\
\
14. Congress and President Trump enacted the Maintaining American Superiority by Improving Export Control Transparency Act (2025-08-19): Updating export control transparency rules aimed to strengthen oversight of sensitive exports while supporting U.S. competitiveness, modestly improving clarity in a key area of economic statecraft.\
\
15. Federal agencies including EPA, FDA, FCC, Census Bureau, GSA, OSHA, and DEA issued numerous routine regulatory notices, approvals, and guidance affecting chemicals, pesticides, medical devices, telecommunications, travel rates, and workplace safety testing (2025-08-19): Ongoing technical rulemakings and data collections across agencies maintained the regulatory infrastructure that shapes environmental standards, consumer protections, and economic activity, largely outside partisan conflict.\
\
